---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import HeroFigure from "../../components/HeroFigure.astro";
import ProgressTimeline from "../../components/ProgressTimeline.astro";
import MarginNote from "../../components/MarginNote.astro";
import MzcCards from "../../components/MzcCards.tsx";
import Exp1Tweety from "../../components/Exp1Tweety.tsx";
import Exp2AgreementTabs from "../../components/Exp2AgreementTabs.tsx";

// Version arc of Paper 1. Collapsed by default to the current version; the full
// history expands on click (ProgressTimeline handles the collapse).
const roadmap = [
  {
    date: "May 2026",
    phase: "v1 · draft",
    title: "Non-circular detection of shortcut reliance",
    summary:
      "The original cut: split “is this variable irrelevant?” into causal irrelevance fixed by construction and training entanglement fixed by measurement — a class taxonomy, a mandatory pure-noise control, and a boundary discipline. Validated as specific, sensitive, and non-vacuous across TF-IDF, DistilBERT, and Qwen-LoRA.",
    href: "/research/sc-certification/v1",
    status: "done",
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "v2 · draft",
    title: "Stable Is Not Grounded — the hierarchy",
    summary:
      "Reframed around a strict hierarchy, accuracy ⊋ stability ⊋ grounding, and a decidability boundary: the grounded/spurious cut needs two-sided observability — a stipulated graph and an auditable training correlation. The same accuracy and stability decompose into opposite grounding verdicts.",
    href: "/research/sc-certification/v2",
    status: "done",
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "v3–v4 · workshop reshape",
    title: "Structure or surface — syntax as the stipulated graph",
    summary:
      "Re-anchored to syntactic structure versus surface cue: grammar supplies the by-construction graph for free, so subject–verb agreement instantiates the same cut without the investigator choosing the shortcut. The exploratory step that became Experiment 2.",
    status: "done",
  },
  {
    date: "Jun 2026",
    phase: "v5 · current",
    title: "One method, two experiments",
    summary:
      "Current v5 draft: one method, two experiments. Experiment 1 is fully auditable; Experiment 2 is an English/German agreement portability diagnosis with a cross-lingual verdict flip. Now tightening scope and the reproducibility package.",
    status: "active",
    color: "var(--accent-coral)",
  },
];
---

<Base title="Stable Is Not Grounded · Xiaochuan Li"
       description="When is a stable, correct answer grounded — and when is it just a shortcut wearing the right answer? A non-circular test, walked through step by step."
       showProgress={true}
       toc={true}>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Workshop paper · current draft · BlackboxNLP target
    </div>
    <h1>Stable Is Not Grounded</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      When is a stable, correct answer <em>grounded</em> — and when is it a shortcut wearing the right answer?
    </p>

    <h2>Roadmap</h2>
    <ProgressTimeline items={roadmap} accent="var(--accent-coral)" />

    <p>
      A model that answers correctly may be doing so for a reason the benchmark never checks. The
      now-standard fix — perturb the input in meaning-preserving ways and see whether the answer
      survives — is one level too shallow. This is the <strong>verdict method the wider modality program
      inherits</strong> — its Certification step, proven here in its first domain (causal structure):
      Leibniz's principle of sufficient reason (<em>nihil est sine ratione</em>) put to a model — does
      a stable, correct answer have a sufficient <em>grounding</em> reason, the structure that licenses
      the conclusion, or only a sufficient <em>predictive</em> one, a surface cue that merely correlates
      with it? Below is the argument as I'd walk through it — the problem, my fix,
      and the two experiments that test it.
    </p>

    <HeroFigure />

    <h2>The usual shortcut argument — and why it's circular</h2>

    <p>
      The standard way to accuse a model of using a shortcut <code>Z</code> goes like this:
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <div class="text-[var(--color-text)]">model is correct on the original item</div>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">change <span class="text-[var(--accent-coral)]">Z</span> &nbsp;→&nbsp; the answer flips</div>
      <div class="text-[var(--color-text)]">∴ the model <span class="text-[var(--accent-coral)]">relies on Z</span></div>
    </div>

    <MarginNote kind="question">
      If severing <code>Z</code> breaks the model, what exactly did it depend on — the shortcut, or
      <em>any</em> edit at all? How would you tell the two apart?
    </MarginNote>

    <p>
      The hidden step is calling <code>Z</code> <em>irrelevant</em>. On a natural benchmark, deciding
      what is irrelevant already needs a theory of the task — and if I pick <code>Z</code> after seeing
      the model fail, the test defines its own conclusion.
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 rounded-md p-4" style="background: rgba(163,45,45,0.08); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-coral);">
      <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider font-medium mb-1" style="color: var(--accent-coral);">Circularity</div>
      <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
        <code class="!text-[var(--color-text)]">Z</code> cannot be called irrelevant <em>only because</em>
        the model failed after we changed it. Irrelevance has to be fixed before we ever look at the model.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>My fix — settle irrelevance before touching the model</h2>

    <p>
      Split the one loaded question — "is <code>Z</code> irrelevant?" — into two that can be answered
      separately, then intervene.
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4">
        <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">Step A</div>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed">Define relevance <strong>independently</strong> — by how I build the item, or by a linguistic rule. Never from model behavior.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4">
        <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">Step B</div>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed">Measure the <strong>training correlation</strong> — which irrelevant cues were actually label-correlated, when the training set is auditable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4">
        <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">Step C</div>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed">Intervene on <code>Z</code>, <code>C</code>, and <code>M</code> — the shortcut, a pure-noise control, and the real structure — and read the pattern.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Three kinds of variable</h2>

    <p>
      Everything turns on telling the shortcut apart from an innocent irrelevant cue. Click each:
    </p>

    <MzcCards client:visible />

    <h2>Experiment 1 — a fully auditable test</h2>

    <p>
      In a controlled "can X fly?" world I author every variable, so relevance and training
      correlation are both known. Press an intervention and compare a grounded model (tracks the
      animal) against a shortcut model (rides color):
    </p>

    <Exp1Tweety client:visible />

    <p>
      Run at scale, the shortcut model reaches <strong>0.912</strong> accuracy and is stable under every
      answer-preserving presentation — it would ship. Severing the color correlation with
      <code>do(Z)</code> drops accuracy by <strong>.408</strong>, while the matched pure-noise control
      <code>do(C)</code> moves only <strong>.021</strong>. The collapse is the shortcut, not fragility —
      the <code>SC-spurious</code> verdict. The same pattern holds across TF-IDF, a 66M encoder, and a
      1.5B decoder (the last on a two-premise chain variant).
    </p>

    <h2>Experiment 2 — the same cut, on real grammar</h2>

    <p>
      Subject–verb agreement settles relevance for free: the verb agrees with the syntactic
      <em>subject</em>, not the nearest noun. So linear proximity is irrelevant by grammar, not by my
      choosing. Switch the slice:
    </p>

    <Exp2AgreementTabs client:visible />

    <MarginNote kind="question">
      Grammar hands me a "right reason" for free. Where else does the structure of a language already
      encode which cue is the licensing one — and which is only nearby?
    </MarginNote>

    <p>
      The headline is a cross-lingual flip: the <em>same</em> model, <code>XGLM-564M</code>, rides
      proximity in English (control − attractor gap <strong>.207</strong>, <code>SC-spurious</code>) but
      tracks the subject in German (gap <strong>.097</strong>, <code>SC-grounded</code>) — the verdict
      inverts with neither model nor task touched, only the language.
    </p>

    <h2>What I can claim — and what I can't</h2>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
      <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: rgba(15,110,86,0.08); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-teal);">
        <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--accent-teal);">Experiment 1 · full test</div>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
          Relevance is fixed by construction <em>and</em> the training data is auditable — so both halves
          of the test are observable. The grounded / spurious verdict is licensed.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: rgba(239,159,39,0.08); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-amber);">
        <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--accent-amber);">Experiment 2 · portability diagnosis</div>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
          Grammar fixes relevance, but the pretraining data is <em>not</em> auditable — the training-correlation
          half goes dark. So I report a portability diagnosis, not a full certificate. Honesty about the boundary
          is the point, not a hedge.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      The deepest cut, <code>SC → {"{grounded, spurious}"}</code>, needs <strong>two-sided
      observability</strong>: a stipulated item graph (benchmark-side) and an auditable training
      correlation (model-side). <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">CAST</a> is built to keep
      the benchmark side observable; on a real benchmark with an opaque-pretrained model, the honest
      decomposition stops one level short, and reporting a "causally grounded" fraction there would be
      underdetermined, not stronger.
    </p>

    <h2>The horizon — a universal language</h2>

    <p>
      Step back, and the goal is the one Leibniz named: a <em>characteristica universalis</em>, a
      language whose surface transparently carries its structure — where the grounding question could
      not even arise, because there would be no surface for an answer to ride. Natural language is the
      opposite: surface and structure come apart, which is exactly what lets a shortcut pass. The
      fully-auditable tasks here are miniature universal characters — built so the surface-to-structure
      map is stipulated and the test stays decidable — and
      <a href="/research/typological-grounding">typological grounding</a> asks how much of that
      structure a real language already supplies. Certification is the first <em>decidable</em> step
      toward that horizon; the longer arc is in <a href="/writing/from-leibniz">the philosophical
      bridge</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Status:</strong> v5 draft — one method, two experiments. Experiment 1 (fully-auditable synthetic, across TF-IDF, DistilBERT, and a Qwen-1.5B LoRA two-premise arm) and Experiment 2 (subject–verb agreement portability, EN + DE, CLAMS zero-shot) are both run and written. BoolQ (boundary case), HANS (naturalistic shortcut witness), and the multi-seed runs are integrated as appendices. Current work: the reproducibility package and tightening the scope statement.</li>
      <li><strong>Target:</strong> BlackboxNLP @ EMNLP 2026 — workshop / methodological position paper.</li>
      <li><strong>Role in the program:</strong> Paper 1. Establishes the <code>accuracy ⊋ stability ⊋ grounding</code> hierarchy and gives a binary certification protocol for stable-correct behavior under construction-and-auditability assumptions.</li>
      <li><strong>Next step:</strong> a <em>fully-licensed</em> agreement experiment — train an agreement model on an auditable corpus so the training-correlation half becomes measurable, upgrading Experiment 2 from a diagnosis to a full certificate.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr />

    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Code and experiments: <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/Stable_is_not_grounded">github.com/xchuan-li/Stable_is_not_grounded</a>.
      Draft available on request — <a href="/contact">/contact</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
